'''Daniel E. Gasman''' (1933 – 19 December 2012)<ref>{{cite news | url=http://historynewsnetwork.org/article/156738 | title=A prominent historian of science dies and no one takes notice| year= 2012 | publisher = History News Network| first=Mehler | last=Barry | accessdate =2015-01-03}}</ref> was an American historian at [[John Jay College]] and the [[CUNY Graduate Center|Graduate Center at City University of New York]].<ref name="CV">{{cite news | url=http://www.ferris.edu/isar/Gasman-cv.pdf | title=Curriculum Vitae | year=2013 | first=Daniel | last=Gasman | accessdate=2013-10-17 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014181636/http://www.ferris.edu/isar/Gasman-cv.pdf | archivedate=2013-10-14 | df= }}</ref> He earned his PhD from [[University of Chicago]] in modern intellectual history.<ref name="CV"/> His most famous book is ''The Scientific Origins of National Socialism'',<ref>For example, see Simon Conway Morris, ''Life’s Solution: Inevitable Humans in a Lonely Universe'' (Cambridge: CUP, 2003) or GJ Stein, "Biological science and the roots of Nazism," [[American Scientist]], Vol. 76, No. 1 1988.</ref> which has been both praised<ref>Robert Herzstein, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1877632 The Scientific Origins of National Socialism by Daniel Gasman]", [[The Journal of Modern History]] Vol. 45, No. 1 (Mar., 1973), pp. 145-147</ref><ref>C. A. Culotta, "The Scientific Origins of National Socialism. Social Darwinism in Ernst Haeckel and the German Monist League by Daniel Gasman", [[Isis (journal)|Isis]], Vol. 63, No. 4 (Dec., 1972), pp. 587-588 </ref><ref>Ralph H. Bowen, "The Scientific Origins of National Socialism: Social Darwinism in Ernst Haeckel and the German [[Monist League]] by Daniel Gasman," [[American Historical Review]], Vol. 78, No. 3 (Jun., 1973), pp. 711-712</ref> and criticized<ref>Richards, Robert J.; [http://home.uchicago.edu/rjr6/articles/Haeckel--antiSemitism.pdf "Ernst Haeckel's Alleged Anti-Semitism and Contributions to Nazi Biology"]</ref> by scholars. His second book, ''Haeckel's Monism and the Birth of Fascist Ideology'', has been reviewed in journals.<ref>Barry Mehler, "Haeckel's Monism and the Birth of Fascist Ideology by Daniel Gasman," [[Journal of the History of Biology]], Vol. 34, No. 1 (Spring, 2001), pp. 207-209</ref><ref>Paul Weindling, "Haeckel's Monism and the Birth of Fascist Ideology by Daniel Gasman," [[The British Journal for the History of Science]], Vol. 35, No. 1 (Mar., 2002), pp. 117-118</ref><ref>[[Roger Griffin]], "Haeckel's Monism and the Birth of Fascist Ideology by Daniel Gasman," [[The English Historical Review]], Vol. 116, No. 467 (Jun., 2001), pp. 683-685</ref><ref>Alexander De Grand, "Haeckel's Monism and the Birth of Fascist Ideology by Daniel Gasman," [[American Historical Review]], Vol. 105, No. 3 (Jun., 2000), pp. 883-884 </ref>
