'''Doro Levi''' (1899–1991) was an [[archaeologist]] who practiced in the [[Mediterranean]] countries in the 20th century.<ref name="NYT">{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CE6DE1439F935A35754C0A967958260|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|title=Obituaries: Doro Levi|accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref>  Specifically, Levi conducted excavations in [[Italy]], [[Greece]], and [[Turkey]]. From 1938 to 1945, Levi was a member of the [[Institute for Advanced Study]] in [[Princeton, New Jersey]].<ref name="NYT"/> Levi has published a number of technical manuscripts on archaeology such as ''Festos e la Civiltà Minoica, tavole I'' published in 1976.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.instapstudycenter.net/L_Library.htm |accessdate=March 3, 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010042838/http://www.instapstudycenter.net/L_Library.htm |archivedate=October 10, 2007 }}</ref>  Some of Levi's most significant work was a long term excavation at [[Minoan civilization|Minoan]] [[Phaistos]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interkriti.org/visits/phaistos.htm |title=Phaistos |publisher=Interkriti.org |date= |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref> which site is the second most significant Minoan [[Human settlement|settlement]] (following [[Knossos]]) and which has yielded important finds such as the [[Phaistos Disk]] and extensive [[Bronze Age]] pottery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://themodernantiquarian.com/site/10857/phaistos.html#fieldnotes |title=Phaistos (Ancient Village / Settlement / Misc. Earthwork) &#124; Greece |publisher=Themodernantiquarian.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref>

